{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's *Sair-e-Falak* (\"Journey through the Sky\"), the speaker embarks on an imaginative celestial voyage beyond the stars and planetary rings, through paradisiacal visions (Tooba's birds, Houris, and the cupbearer Saqian), into a frozen cosmic void revealed as Hell.[^1] The central vision-moment arrives when the angel Surosh explains this bleak realm: Hell lacks inherent fire or light—damned souls import their own \"embers\" from earthly deeds, rendering punishment self-inflicted.[^2] The speaker seeks transcendent insight into cosmic and spiritual realities, particularly the self-determining nature of the soul across divine realms.\n\nIn the Old English *Wanderer*, the speaker (\"earth-stepper,\" \"lone-dweller\") traverses frozen exile-paths across rime-cold seas amid storms, hail, and encroaching darkness, haunted by memories of lost lords, kinsmen, and hall-joys; visions of sea-birds and ruined \"wind-blown walls\" evoke middle-earth's cosmic decay under Wyrd and the Fates.[^3] The central vision-moment fuses dream (clasping a lost liege-lord) with awakening to this transience, yielding wisdom: true stability lies in seeking \"grace\" and \"comfort from the Father in heaven.\"[^4] The speaker hopes to find mercy, a new treasure-giver (lord), or ultimately divine consolation amid inevitable loss.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch.18 (*Sair-e-Falak*), [translation](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch.18 (*Sair-e-Falak*), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/#p-3ccdfb).\n[^3]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch.11 (*The Wanderer*), [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n[^4]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch.11 (*The Wanderer*), [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-5bdc65).",
